== Infrastructure ==
=== Roads ===
[[Automobile|Car]] ownership in Iceland is among the highest in the world, although Reykjav<U+00ED>k is not severely affected by [[congestion]] as the city is rather spread out. Wide multi-lane highways run all over the city connecting the different neighbourhoods and suburbs. Parking spaces are also plentiful in most areas. Public transportation only exists in the form of a bus system (called '[[Str<U+00E6>t<U+00F3> bs]]) and is not very popular in this car friendly city. [[Route 1 (Iceland)|Route 1]] (the Ring Road) runs by the city outskirts and connects it to the rest of Iceland.

=== Airports and seaports ===
[[Reykjav<U+00ED>k Airport]], the second largest [[airport]] in the country (after [[Keflav<U+00ED>k International Airport]]), is positioned inside the city, just south of the city centre. It is mainly used for domestic flights as well as flights to [[Greenland]] and the [[Faroe Islands]]. It was built there by the [[United Kingdom|British]] occupation force during [[World War II]] on the outskirts of, then much smaller, Reykjav<U+00ED>k. In later years there has been some controversy regarding the location of the airport since it takes up a lot of valuable space in central Reykjav<U+00ED>k.

Reykjav<U+00ED>k has two [[seaport]]s, the old harbour near the city centre which is mainly used by [[Fisheries|fishermen]] and [[Cruise ship]]s and ''Sundah<U+00F6>fn'' in the east city which is the largest [[cargo]] port in the country.

===Heating===
Most houses in Reykjav<U+00ED>k use the [[geothermal heating]] system. It is the largest system of this kind in the world. See [[geothermal power in Iceland]].

